Ah! Now I understand your issue more clearly. The ‚ÄúERR_CONNECTION_TIMED_OUT‚Äù means your browser cannot reach the server at all, not that there‚Äôs a Flask or Nginx misconfiguration. That‚Äôs why you don‚Äôt see any warnings‚Äîyour request isn‚Äôt even reaching Nginx.

Here‚Äôs why this could happen and how to check/fix it:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Firewall / UFW on the server
On Ubuntu, the default firewall may block port 443.

Check the status:

sudo ufw status
If it‚Äôs active, allow HTTPS:

sudo ufw allow 443/tcp
sudo ufw allow 80/tcp
sudo ufw reload
2Ô∏è‚É£ Nginx is listening only on IPv4
Check if Nginx is bound correctly:

sudo ss -tulnp | grep 443
You should see something like:

LISTEN 0 128 0.0.0.0:443 0.0.0.0:* users:(("nginx",pid,...))
If it‚Äôs 127.0.0.1:443, external clients cannot connect.

Fix: in /etc/nginx/sites-available/simple-login, make sure:

listen 443 ssl;
# not listen 127.0.0.1:443;
Then restart Nginx:

sudo systemctl restart nginx
3Ô∏è‚É£ Network / NAT issues
Is the browser on the same local network as 192.168.0.128?

If yes, ping the server from the browser machine:

ping 192.168.0.128
If ping fails ‚Üí network issue (wrong IP, firewall on router, or machine offline).

4Ô∏è‚É£ Testing from the server itself
From the server, try:

curl -vk https://192.168.0.128/login
If it works ‚Üí Flask + Nginx are fine, problem is network/firewall.

If it times out ‚Üí Nginx is not reachable externally.

‚úÖ Most likely causes:

UFW / iptables blocking port 443

Nginx listening only on localhost

The machine running Flask/Nginx is on a different subnet than your client

