ChatGPT said:
Got it! You want your Windows browsers to fully trust the self-signed certificate so you won‚Äôt get SSL warnings. Here‚Äôs a step-by-step guide:

1. Copy your certificate to Windows
On your Linux server, your certificate file is at:

/etc/ssl/localcerts/webapp.crt
Copy this .crt file to your Windows machine. You can use:

SCP, WinSCP, or just a USB drive.

Make sure it‚Äôs in a location you can easily access, e.g., C:\Users\<YourUser>\Downloads\webapp.crt.

2. Open Certificate Manager on Windows
Press Win + R ‚Üí type:

certmgr.msc
‚Üí Press Enter.
This opens Certificate Manager for the current user.

Or, for system-wide trust (all users):

Press Win + R ‚Üí type:

mmc
File ‚Üí Add/Remove Snap-in ‚Üí Certificates ‚Üí Computer account ‚Üí Local computer ‚Üí Finish ‚Üí OK.

3. Import the certificate
Navigate to:

Trusted Root Certification Authorities ‚Üí Certificates
Right-click Certificates ‚Üí All Tasks ‚Üí Import.

Follow the wizard:

Browse and select webapp.crt you copied.

Store it in Trusted Root Certification Authorities.

Finish the wizard.

4. Confirm and restart browser
You should see the certificate listed under Trusted Root Certification Authorities ‚Üí Certificates.

Close and reopen your browser.

Now go to:

https://192.168.0.128/login
The SSL warning should disappear.

üí° Tip: If you want to make it work for all browsers (Chrome, Edge, Firefox):

Chrome/Edge ‚Üí use Windows cert store (above).

Firefox ‚Üí has its own certificate store, so you may need to import there too:

Options ‚Üí Privacy & Security ‚Üí View Certificates ‚Üí Authorities ‚Üí Import.

If you want, I can give a super simple command to export your Linux cert in .crt format ready for Windows so you can just double-click to install.

